{"lc": 1, "type": "constructor", "id": ["langchain", "schema", "document", "Document"], "kwargs": {"metadata": {"producer": "Canva", "creator": "Canva", "creationdate": "2023-07-06T19:39:51+00:00", "author": "Erin Human", "keywords": "DAFYyrGwRvQ,BAEwAah4POg", "moddate": "2023-10-05T07:12:00-05:00", "title": "A Neurodiversity and Gentle Parenting Journey\u2026in Color", "source": "corpus\\A-Neurodiversity-and-Gentle-Parenting-Journey.-in-Color.final_.pdf", "total_pages": 134, "page": 18, "page_label": "19"}, "page_content": "the BACB (the body that is responsible for the accreditation of ABA\nprograms and personnel). I watched some videos and webinars. I\nread various articles. I looked at even more research.\nAnd I wasn\u2019t feeling it.\nBC (before children) I had taken some undergraduate level psych-\nology courses in college. I took more of them than what was required\nof my degree because I found the courses interesting, using the extra\nclasses as electives. Aside from the usual intro to psychology survey\nclasses I also took some courses in child psychology, developmental\npsychology (over the lifespan), social psychology, women\u2019s psych-\nology, etc. While I do not profess that taking a handful of classes\nmakes me any sort of expert in psychology, it seemed to me that this\n40 hour a week ABA recommendation was contrary to nearly every-\nthing that I\u2019d learned about development and the young child.\nI mean, 40 hours/week is the equivalent of a full-time job!", "type": "Document"}}